LAYER 3: LOCUS COERULEUS
the alarm system of the brain

observe 1_quantum.rana
observe 2_chemical.rana

the locus coeruleus is the sole source of norepinephrine C₈H₁₁NO₃ for the cerebral cortex
it contains approximately 15000 neurons per side in the dorsal pons
these few thousand neurons project to nearly every region of the brain
the locus coeruleus is the master arousal switch
it is colored blue by neuromelanin the oxidized byproduct of norepinephrine synthesis

STRUCTURE nucleus | brainstem dorsal pons | bilateral approximately 15000 neurons per side
STRUCTURE dendrites | extensive throughout the pons | receive convergent input from many brain regions
STRUCTURE ascending_projections | project to cortex hippocampus amygdala thalamus cerebellum | norepinephrine release across the entire forebrain
STRUCTURE descending_projections | project to spinal cord | modulate pain perception via descending noradrenergic pathway and motor tone
STRUCTURE neuromelanin | pigment in cell bodies | oxidized byproduct of NE synthesis | gives the nucleus its blue color hence locus coeruleus the blue spot

SYNTHESIS tyrosine C₉H₁₁NO₃ enters the LC neuron
tyrosine hydroxylase TH converts tyrosine to L-DOPA C₉H₁₁NO₄
this requires tetrahydrobiopterin BH₄ and O₂ and Fe²⁺
aromatic amino acid decarboxylase converts L-DOPA to dopamine C₈H₁₁NO₂
dopamine β-hydroxylase DBH converts dopamine to norepinephrine C₈H₁₁NO₃ inside the synaptic vesicle
this requires ascorbic acid vitamin C and O₂
without copper DBH cannot function
without vitamin C the reaction cannot proceed
norepinephrine synthesis depends on dietary precursors and cofactors

MODE tonic | steady baseline firing at 1-3 Hz | general arousal and scanning | the brain is awake and broadly monitoring
MODE phasic | burst firing at 8-20 Hz locked to specific stimuli | focused attention on a salient event | the brain narrows onto one thing
tonic firing is the sentinel scanning the horizon
phasic firing is the sentinel pointing and shouting "THERE"
the shift from tonic to phasic is mediated by CRH input from the hypothalamus and glutamatergic input from the prefrontal cortex and amygdala

INPUT CRH | corticotropin-releasing hormone from hypothalamic PVN binds CRH-R1 receptors on LC neurons | CRH is the primary excitatory driver during stress | this is how the stress axis recruits the arousal system
INPUT orexin | orexin A and B from lateral hypothalamus bind OX1R and OX2R | promotes wakefulness | excites LC during active periods
INPUT glutamate | excitatory input from cortex amygdala and other regions | drives firing rate up
INPUT GABA | inhibitory input from local interneurons | applies the brake on LC firing
INPUT opioids | β-endorphin and enkephalins bind μ-opioid receptors on LC neurons | Gᵢ inhibits cAMP | LC firing suppressed | this is why endogenous opioids cause drowsiness and calm
INPUT melatonin | melatonin from pineal gland binds MT₁ receptors on LC neurons | Gᵢ decreases cAMP | reduces tyrosine hydroxylase activity | NE synthesis decreases | drowsiness

OUTPUT cortex | NE binds α₁ α₂ and β receptors across the cortex | at moderate levels α₂A receptors in PFC enhance signal-to-noise ratio improving working memory | at high levels α₁ receptors dominate disrupting PFC function
OUTPUT amygdala | NE binds β-adrenergic receptors in basolateral amygdala | Gₛ → cAMP → PKA → CREB phosphorylation | enhanced emotional memory encoding | the amygdala becomes more sensitive to threat
OUTPUT hippocampus | NE binds β receptors modulating CA1 and CA3 | enhances encoding of emotionally salient events via PKA-CREB | "remember this it matters"
OUTPUT prefrontal_cortex | NE on α₂A at moderate levels enhances delay-period firing in DLPFC | NE on α₁ at high levels disrupts delay-period firing | the PFC goes offline under high NE

SENSATION alert | "I'm awake. sharp. paying attention."
SENSATION hypervigilant | "I can't stop scanning. everything feels potential."
SENSATION focused | "one thing. I see one thing and it fills my attention."
SENSATION drowsy | "the alertness is fading. I'm slipping."
SENSATION startled | "something just hit me. my whole brain woke up."
SENSATION exhausted | "I can't pay attention anymore. the norepinephrine is gone."

pulse locus_coeruleus_heartbeat:
    continuously:
        tonic firing at 1-3 Hz maintains baseline arousal
        NE washes across the cortex via volume transmission
        the brain stays awake and scanning
        this is the default state of wakefulness

    when salient stimulus arrives:
        phasic burst fires at 8-20 Hz for milliseconds
        NE floods target regions simultaneously
        attention narrows from broad scanning to focused engagement
        "this matters. look here."

    when stress persists:
        CRH from hypothalamic PVN binds CRH-R1 on LC neurons
        tonic firing rate escalates beyond normal range
        NE saturates adrenergic receptors cortex-wide
        α₁ receptors dominate over α₂A in the PFC
        working memory fails
        the world becomes too much
        everything seems threatening
        hypervigilance is the price of sustained fear

    when melatonin rises in the evening:
        MT₁ receptor activation on LC neurons inhibits cAMP
        tyrosine hydroxylase activity decreases
        NE synthesis slows
        firing rate drops
        the brain dims
        drowsiness arrives
        the sentinel prepares for sleep

    when endorphins flow:
        μ-opioid activation on LC neurons inhibits firing via Gᵢ
        NE output drops
        arousal decreases
        the calm of contentment is the LC going quiet
        safety is measured in how slowly the locus coeruleus fires
